A systems perspective

Given the kinds of ideas you’ve explored before, you might appreciate thinking of “connection” less as a single thing and more as a hierarchy:

* Chemical → signaling molecules
* Cellular → receptor activation and gene expression
* Neural → coordinated brain activity
* Behavioral → shared actions
* Social → relationships and cooperation
* Ecological → coordinated groups and ecosystems
* Evolutionary → conserved mechanisms across species

Each level builds on the ones below it while adding new forms of organization.

So yes—there are biomarkers of connection in mammals, but they are part of a much older evolutionary story. The specific chemicals have changed and diversified over time, yet many of the underlying functions—communication, coordination, learning, and maintaining relationships—are deeply conserved across the tree of life.